IAM Roles:
  - IAM role is an IAM identity that you can create in your account that has specific permissions.
  - IAM role is similar to an IAM user, in that it is an AWS identity with permission policies that determine what the identity can and cannot do in AWS.
  - However, instead of being uniquely associated with one person.
  - IAM identity that you can create in your account that has specific permissions.
  - Roles can be used by the following:

    An IAM user in the same AWS account as the role
    An IAM user in a different AWS account than the role
    A web service offered by AWS such as Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2)
    An external user authenticated by an external identity provider (IdP) service that is compatible with SAML 2.0 or OpenID Connect, or a custom-built identity broker.
  - IAM allows you to manage users and their level of access to the AWS console
  - Centralised control your AWS account
  - Shared access to your AWS account.
  - granular permission.
  - identity fedration.
  - Multifactor authentication.
  - provide temporry access to user and services,
  - allow you to set up your own password rotation policy

  